library(mvnfast)
library(MCMCpack)
## Loading required package: coda
## Loading required package: MASS
## ##
## ## Markov Chain Monte Carlo Package (MCMCpack)
## ## Copyright (C) 2003-2025 Andrew D. Martin, Kevin M. Quinn, and Jong Hee Park
## ##
## ## Support provided by the U.S. National Science Foundation
## ## (Grants SES-0350646 and SES-0350613)
## ##
spotify <- read.csv("/Users/jacqueline/Documents/Spring2025/DS4420/HW7/ds4420_spotify.csv")
spotify <- spotify[-107, ]
spotify$explicit <- as.integer(spotify$explicit)
spotify <- spotify[, !(names(spotify) %in% c("song_title", "artist_name"))]

# Standardize selected features
features_to_scale <- c("release_month", "release_year", "artist_pop", "duration_s")
spotify[features_to_scale] <- scale(spotify[features_to_scale])

y <- spotify$track_pop
X <- as.matrix(cbind(1, spotify[, c("release_month", "release_year", "artist_pop", "duration_s", "explicit")]))
colnames(X)[1] <- "intercept"

# Train-test split (80-20)
set.seed(42)
n <- nrow(X)
train_idx <- sample(1:n, size = 0.8 * n)
X_train <- X[train_idx, ]
y_train <- y[train_idx]
X_test <- X[-train_idx, ]
y_test <- y[-train_idx]
# Prior setup
d <- ncol(X_train)
prior_w <- matrix(0, nrow = d, ncol = 1)
prior_Sigma <- diag(d) * 10
prior_alpha <- 3
prior_beta <- 1
# Gibbs sampling
n_iter <- 10000
gibbs_samples_w <- matrix(0, nrow = n_iter, ncol = d)
gibbs_samples_sigmay <- numeric(n_iter)

w_tilde <- matrix(0, nrow = d, ncol = 1)
sigma2_tilde <- 1

for (i in 1:n_iter) {
  V <- solve((1 / sigma2_tilde) * t(X_train) %*% X_train + solve(prior_Sigma))
  M <- V %*% ((1 / sigma2_tilde) * t(X_train) %*% y_train + solve(prior_Sigma) %*% prior_w)
  w_tilde <- t(rmvn(1, mu = M, sigma = V))
  
  A <- (2 * prior_alpha + length(y_train)) / 2
  B <- (2 * prior_beta + t(y_train - X_train %*% w_tilde) %*% (y_train - X_train %*% w_tilde)) / 2
  sigma2_tilde <- rinvgamma(1, shape = A, scale = B)
  
  gibbs_samples_w[i, ] <- w_tilde
  gibbs_samples_sigmay[i] <- sigma2_tilde
}
# Traceplot and ACF for intercept
plot(gibbs_samples_w[, 1], type = "l", main = "Traceplot for Intercept", xlab = "Iteration", ylab = "Value")

acf(gibbs_samples_w[, 1], main = "ACF for Intercept")

# Posterior of variance
hist(gibbs_samples_sigmay, main = "Posterior of Variance", xlab = "Value", col = "lightgreen")

# Posterior distributions of coefficients in a grid
par(mfrow = c(2, 3))
for (j in 1:d) {
  hist(gibbs_samples_w[, j], main = paste("Posterior of", colnames(X_train)[j]), xlab = "Value", col = "lightblue")
}

par(mfrow = c(1, 1))

# Posterior predictive sampling
post_w <- gibbs_samples_w[(n_iter - 999):n_iter, ]
post_sigma2 <- gibbs_samples_sigmay[(n_iter - 999):n_iter]

pred_samples <- matrix(0, nrow = 1000, ncol = nrow(X_test))
for (i in 1:1000) {
  mean_pred <- X_test %*% matrix(post_w[i, ], ncol = 1)
  pred_samples[i, ] <- rnorm(nrow(X_test), mean = mean_pred, sd = sqrt(post_sigma2[i]))
}
pred_means <- colMeans(pred_samples)

# Predicted vs Actual plot
plot(y_test, pred_means, main = "Predicted vs Actual Track Popularity",
     xlab = "Actual", ylab = "Predicted", pch = 19, col = "blue")
abline(a = 0, b = 1, col = "red", lwd = 2)

# Correlation between predictions and true values
cor(y_test, pred_means)
## [1] 0.674319

b - set the prior mean for w to 0 and the prior covariance matrix Sigma_0 to 10 times the identity matrix this represents weakly informative priors suitable for standardized inputs.

  1. used an inverse gamma prior for sigma squared with alpha_0 equal to 3 and beta_0 equal to 1, which implies a prior mean of 0.5. This balances prior belief with flexibility to adapt based on the data.

c - The traceplot and autocorrelation function show that the chain mixes well and stabilizes quickly. Since there is no significant drift and the autocorrelations drop off fast, burn-in and thinning are not necessary in this case.

d - The posterior histograms show that explicit, artist_pop, and the intercept have noticeable impact since their weights are far from zero. Weights close to zero, such as for release_year, suggest that these features may not significantly influence track popularity.

e - i. The predicted versus actual plot shows a clear positive trend, suggesting that the model captures general patterns in the data even if it misses some individual points. ii. The correlation between predictions and true values is 0.7, indicating a moderately strong predictive performance. iii. The model does a fairly good job predicting track popularity, capturing key trends and providing useful estimates.

# Reconstruct training data as a data frame for brm
spotify_train <- data.frame(y = y_train, X_train)
colnames(spotify_train)[1] <- "track_pop"

# Define the formula
formula <- bf(track_pop ~ release_month + release_year + artist_pop + duration_s + explicit)

# Use default priors
prior <- default_prior(formula, data = spotify_train, family = gaussian())

# Fit Bayesian linear regression using brm
fit_brm <- brm(
  formula = formula,
  data = spotify_train,
  family = gaussian(),
  chains = 4,
  iter = 10000,
  warmup = 1800,
  prior = prior,
  seed = 42
)

spotify$track_pop <- y
spotify$intercept <- NULL
spotify_train <- spotify[train_idx, ]
spotify_test <- spotify[-train_idx, ]

# newdata = spotify_test
post_preds_brm <- posterior_predict(fit_brm, newdata = spotify_test)

# Take the mean of posterior predictions for each observation
pred_means_brm <- colMeans(post_preds_brm)

#  predicted vs actual
plot(y_test, pred_means_brm, main = "Predicted vs Actual (brm)",
     xlab = "Actual", ylab = "Predicted", pch = 19, col = "blue")

# Correlation
